<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Dahlbom realized that this specimen does not have an &quot;exotic&quot; habitus (Bengala was the old name of a district between NW India and Bangladesh) and 
<pageBreakToken pageId="19" pageNumber="20" start="start">cited</pageBreakToken>
the type locality as &quot;forte Bengalia&quot; [accidentally Bengalia for Bengala]. The species is distributed in North Africa and Near East (
<bibRefCitation pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Linsenmaier 1999</bibRefCitation>
: 218). The type is missing the ventral surface of the metasoma, due to a dermestid attack. It belongs to the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Masaridae" genus="Chrysis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysis ignita" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignita">Chrysis ignita</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
